# aka-claude-tools.config — opt-in, environment-specific policy for the guard hooks
# ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# This file tunes two aka-claude-tools hooks to YOUR environment. It ships with
# every value empty, so the hooks are no-ops until you set something here — the
# kit never assumes anything about your org, network, or tooling.
#
#   WHAT THIS IS   — policy and patterns: what to redact, what to steer away from.
#   WHAT IT IS NOT — a place for secrets. Nothing here is a credential. These are
#                    the patterns that keep credentials and internal details from
#                    leaking — never the secrets themselves.
#
# How it's loaded (first hit wins):
#   1. $CLAUDETOOLS_CONFIG                          explicit override
#   2. $CLAUDE_CONFIG_DIR/aka-claude-tools.config   your active profile
#   3. ~/.claude/aka-claude-tools.config            default profile
#
# It's a shell file (`KEY="value"`, sourced by bash) and is restored automatically
# across `install.sh` upgrades — set it once. To use it:
#   cp aka-claude-tools.config.example "$CLAUDE_CONFIG_DIR/aka-claude-tools.config"
# then uncomment what you need below.


# ── leak-guard.sh — keep internal details from leaving the building ─
# Threat model: an agent pastes an internal hostname, IP, username, absolute home
# path, or unreleased codename into a *web search/fetch* query or an *outbound*
# shell command (curl/wget/nc/…), quietly handing your topology to a third party.
# This is a per-environment denylist of identifiers that must never egress; a hit
# blocks the query/command before it leaves.
#
# CT_EGRESS_PATTERNS — ONE extended-regex (ERE), pipe-separated alternatives.
# Substring match, case-sensitive; escape any literal dots. Categories to mix:
#
#   internal / tailnet domains   acme\.internal | [a-z0-9-]+\.ts\.net
#   RFC1918 + CGNAT ranges       10\.[0-9]+\.[0-9]+\.[0-9]+ | 192\.168\.[0-9]+\.[0-9]+
#                                100\.(6[4-9]|[7-9][0-9]|1[01][0-9]|12[0-7])\.   # tailscale 100.64/10
#   VCS / SSO usernames          acme-vcs-bot | jdoe@acme
#   absolute home paths          /Users/jdoe/ | /home/jdoe/
#   unreleased codenames         project-bluejay | falcon-rewrite
#
# Example (one line — combine the categories you care about):
#   CT_EGRESS_PATTERNS='acme\.internal|[a-z0-9-]+\.ts\.net|10\.[0-9]+\.[0-9]+\.[0-9]+|/Users/jdoe/|project-bluejay'
CT_EGRESS_PATTERNS=""


# ── harness-pointer.sh — steer the agent to the right tool for THIS environment ─
# When an agent reaches for a command that's wrong here — not installed, not
# authenticated, or simply not how your team works — intercept it and hand back
# the correct approach, instead of letting it fail confusingly and thrash through
# retries. GUIDANCE, not a security boundary: it matches only the first word, so
# `sudo <cmd>` and pipes slip past — real restrictions belong in
# settings.json `permissions.deny`.
#
# CT_BLOCKED_CMDS — ERE alternation of command names (first word) to intercept.
# CT_BLOCKED_HINT — the message returned to the agent on a match. Make it
#                   ACTIONABLE: say what to do instead, not just "no".
#
# Example — GitHub over SSH, no API token on the box (a least-privilege git
# posture: auth is scoped to git transport only, and there's no broad gh token to
# steal or pivot through):
#   CT_BLOCKED_CMDS="gh"
#   CT_BLOCKED_HINT="gh isn't authenticated here — this environment uses SSH to GitHub. Use git over SSH for clone/fetch/push, and open PRs from the branch's compare page: https://github.com/<owner>/<repo>/compare/main...<branch>?expand=1 (derive <owner>/<repo> from 'git remote get-url origin')."
#
# Example — self-hosted VCS, the GitHub CLI simply doesn't apply:
#   CT_BLOCKED_CMDS="gh"
#   CT_BLOCKED_HINT="Use plain git — this team's remote is self-hosted, not GitHub."
#
# Example — keep agents off production tooling, push them to a guarded wrapper:
#   CT_BLOCKED_CMDS="kubectl|helm"
#   CT_BLOCKED_HINT="Don't touch the cluster directly — use ./scripts/deploy (it pins the context and requires an approval)."
#
# Example — enforce a toolchain choice:
#   CT_BLOCKED_CMDS="npm|npx|yarn"
#   CT_BLOCKED_HINT="This repo standardises on bun — use bun / bunx instead."
CT_BLOCKED_CMDS=""
CT_BLOCKED_HINT="This command isn't the right tool in this environment (aka-claude-tools harness-pointer) — see aka-claude-tools.config for the intended approach."
